{{Infobox writer | name = Henri Bresc | image = | imagesize = | caption = | pseudonym = | birth_name = | birth_date = 12 December 1939{{r|ocean}} | birth_place = [[Cannes]], France{{r|ocean}} | death_date = | death_place = | occupation = Historian | nationality = French | period = | genre = | subject = [[Mediaeval history]] | movement = | notableworks = | influences = | influenced = | signature = | website = }}
'''Henri Bresc''' (born 12 December 1939) is a French historian who specialises in the [[Mediaeval history]] of Sicily, and particularly in the inter-relation in the Mediterranean area between the three principal [[monotheistic]] religions.{{r|mule|iesr}} From 1990 until 2008 he was a professor at [[Paris X Nanterre]] university,{{r|iesr}} and is director of its Centre d'Histoire Sociale et Culturelle de l'Occident.{{r|abdel|page=153|ocean}} He previously taught at the [[University of Nice]].{{r|ocean}}
In 2002 Bresc received an [[honorary degree]] in [[Literature|letters]] from the [[University of Palermo]].{{r|mule}}
== Works ==
Among Bresc's many publications are:{{r|ocean}}
* ''Livre et société en Sicile (1299-1499)''. Palermo: Centro di Studi Filologici e Linguistici Siciliani, 1971 * ''La Correspondance de Pierre Ameilh, archevêque de Naples, puis d'Embrun (1363-1369)''. Paris: Centre National de la Recherche Scientifique, 1972 * ''Un monde méditerranéen: économie et société en Sicile (1300-1460)''. Rome: Ecole française de Rome, 1986 * ''Idrîsî: La première géographie de l'Occident''. Paris: Garnier-Flammarion, 1999 (with Annliese Nef) * ''Arabes de langue, Juifs de religion. L'évolution du judaïsme sicilien dans l'environnement latin, XIIe -XVe siècles''. Saint-Denis: Bouchène, 2001 **Italian edition: ''Arabi per lingua, ebrei per religione''. Messina: GEM, 2001
