== [[35th century BCE]] == {| class="wikitable" style="width:100%;" |- ! style="width:6%" | Year || style="width:10%" | Date || Event |- | 3300 BCE || || Phase of the [[Indus Valley Civilization]] begins. The civilization used an early form of the Indus signs, the so-called [[Indus script]]. Over the course of next 1000–1500 years, inhabitants of the Civilization developed new techniques in handicraft ([[carnelian]] products, seal carving) and metallurgy (copper, bronze, lead, and tin) had elaborate urban planning, baked brick houses, efficient drainage systems, water supply systems, and clusters of large non-residential buildings.{{Sfn|Wright|2010|pp=115–125}} The civilization depended significantly on trade, was the first civilization to use wheeled transport in form of bullock carts, and also used boats.<ref>Hasenpflug, Rainer, The Inscriptions of the Indus civilisation Norderstedt, Germany, 2006.</ref> |- |}
== [[27th century BCE]] == {| class="wikitable" style="width:100%;" |- ! style="width:6%" | Year || style="width:10%" | Date || Event |- |2600 BCE || || The cities of Harappa and Mohenjo-daro become large metropolises and the civilization expands to over 2,500 cities and settlements across the whole of Pakistan, much of northern India, and large parts of Afghanistan,<ref>{{cite book|author=Robert Greenberger|title=A Historical Atlas of Pakistan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RukebrLEpi4C&pg=PA5|year=2003|publisher=The Rosen Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-8239-3866-7|page=5}}</ref> covering a region of around one million square miles, which was larger than the land area of its contemporaries Egypt and Mesopotamia combined, and also had superior urban planning and sewage systems. The civilization began using the mature Indus script for its writing system. |- |2600 BCE || || End of the Early Dynastic II Period and the beginning of the Early Dynastic IIIa Period in Mesopotamia. |- |2900 BCE – 2334 BCE|| || Mesopotamian wars of the Early Dynastic period. |}
