{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}} :''For the Scottish inventor, see [[William Kennedy Dickson]].'' [[File:1 and 3 Darnaway Street, Edinburgh.jpg|thumb|1 and 3 Darnaway Street, Edinburgh]] [[File:The grave of William Kirk Dickson, Grange Cemetery, Edinburgh.jpg|thumb|The grave of William Kirk Dickson, Grange Cemetery, Edinburgh]] '''William Kirk Dickson''' (1860 – 14 July 1949) was a Scottish [[advocate]], librarian and writer. He was Keeper of the [[Advocates' Library]] from 1906–25, and Librarian of the [[National Library of Scotland]] from 1925–31.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nls.uk/help/biogs.html|title=The First Reader's Ticket&nbsp;– Brief biographies|publisher=National Library of Scotland|accessdate=18 September 2010}}</ref>
==Life== He was born in Edinburgh, the son of Anne and William Dickson of Mauricewood.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nls.uk/guides/biogs|title=Biographies - William Dickson - Donald Ross|last=|first=|date=1925-10-26|website=National Library of Scotland|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|accessdate=2017-02-28}}</ref>
He studied law at [[University of Edinburgh]] and qualified as an advocate in 1887.
In the late 19th century he lived at 3 Darnaway Street on the [[Moray Estate]] in western Edinburgh.<ref>Edinburgh and Leith Post Office Directory 1899-1900</ref>
In 1912 [[University of St Andrews]] granted him an honorary doctorate, [[Legum Doctor|LL.D]].
He died in [[Edinburgh]] on 14 July 1949 and is buried with his parents in the [[Grange, Edinburgh|Grange Cemetery]] in the south of the city. The grave lies against the south wall. His wife Kathleen Murdoch lies with him, as does his son, Rear Admiral Robert Kirk Dickson (1898-1952).
His youngest son, Archibald William Dickson, was killed in the [[Battle of Jutland]], when [[HMS Queen Mary|HMS ''Queen Mary'']] was destroyed by [[SMS Derfflinger|SMS ''Derfflinger'']], aged 16.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://digital.nls.uk/great-war/schools/downloads/archibald-w-dickson-case-study.pdf|title=Experiences of the Great War : Case study: Archibald William Dickson|last=|first=|date=|website=National Library of Scotland|format=PDF|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|accessdate=2017-02-28}}</ref>
